# helper function to read qualtrics csv data
# note: must add option to remove linebreaks when downloading
# see here: https://stackoverflow.com/a/50314806
read_qualtrics <- function(filename) {
    headers <- read_csv(filename, col_names = FALSE, n_max = 1)
    qualtrics <- read_csv(filename, skip = 3, col_names = FALSE)
    colnames(qualtrics) <- headers
    qualtrics$filename <- filename
    qualtrics
}

# helper function to batch read mturk csv data
# forces survey codes to be numeric
read_mturk_with_numeric_surveycode <- function(filename) {
    mturk <- read.csv(filename) %>%
        mutate(Answer.surveycode = as.numeric(as.character(Answer.surveycode)))
}

# helper function to display table in html format
display_table <- function(table) {
    table %>% kable("html") %>% as.character() %>% display_html()
}

In [9]:
check_correct <- function(response, actual) {
    response >= (1 - margin)*actual & response <= (1 + margin)*actual
}

check_identical <- function(response, actual) {
    as.numeric(response) == as.numeric(actual)
}

# convert data to long format: every row is one response for one question
df_long <- df %>%
    select(ResponseId,
           condition,
           matches(response_cols_matcher)) %>% 
    pivot_longer(matches(response_cols_matcher),
                 values_to = "response") %>%
    extract(name, c("question_type", "question"), '(recall|calculate)_(.*)') %>%
    left_join(exact_values)

# check response correctness and googling behaviors
df_long <- df_long %>%
    mutate(
        is_correct_exact = mapply(check_correct, `response`, `actual_exact`),
        is_correct_round = mapply(check_correct, `response`, `actual_approx`),
        is_identical_exact = mapply(check_identical, `response`, `actual_exact`),
        is_identical_round = mapply(check_identical, `response`, `actual_approx`),
        is_identical_recall = ifelse(condition == 'Saw precise numbers', is_identical_exact, is_identical_round)
    )

Joining, by = c("question_type", "question")

Remove participants who failed the screening comprehension test twice¶

We had participants read about what they are supposed to do and not do during the study. Then they had to select all the options that apply. We will remove participants who did not select all the correct options.

In [11]:
get_comprehension_performance <- function(fail_first, fail_second) {
    if (is.na(fail_first)) {
        'pass first check'
    } else if (is.na(fail_second)) {
        'pass second check'
    } else {
        'fail second check'
    }
}
df <- df %>%
    mutate(comprehension_performance = mapply(get_comprehension_performance, `fail_first_attention`, `fail_second_attention`))

In [12]:
comprehension_score <- function(response) {
    # +1 point for selecting the correct options
    score <- to_vec(for(opt in correct_comprehension_options) grepl(opt, response, fixed=TRUE)) %>% sum()
    # +1 point for not selecting the incorrect option
    score + !grepl(incorrect_comprehension_option, response, fixed=TRUE)
}
                    
excluded_participants <- df %>% filter(comprehension_performance == 'fail second check')
                    
excluded_participants %>%
    mutate(comprehension_score = mapply(comprehension_score, `attention_check_2`)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = comprehension_score)) + geom_histogram(bins = 5) +
    labs(title = sprintf("Distribution of comprehension scores of people who failed the second check"), x = "Comprehension score")

Design¶

This was a randomized experiment with two conditions: precise and round. First people read three news articles. In the precise condition, the numbers were set to 3-7 significant digits. In the round condition the numbers were set to 1 significant digit. Then participants were asked to recall the numbers from the articles and performed calculations on the recalled numbers. These two tasks are identical in both conditions.

# general function to construct a histogram of responses ranges in each condition
plot_responses_by_condition <- function(qtype, qid, x_label, title, scale_log10 = TRUE) {
    exact_value <- filter(exact_values, qtype == question_type & question == qid)$actual_exact[1]
    data_col <- sprintf("%s_%s", qtype, qid)
    histogram <- ggplot(df, aes(x = !!sym(data_col))) +
        geom_histogram() +
        geom_vline(xintercept = exact_value, linetype = 'dashed', color = 'red') +
        facet_wrap(~ condition, ncol = 1, scale = "free_y") +
        labs(
            x = x_label,
            y = "Number of responses",
            title = title,
            subtitle = sprintf('Actual was %s', as.character(exact_value))
        )
    if (scale_log10) {
        histogram + scale_x_log10(label = comma)
    } else {
        histogram
    }
}

# general function to compute the percentage of responses that are within 10% of the exact value
compute_correct_percentages <- function(data_col, exact_value, margin) {
    df %>%
      mutate(approx_correct = !!sym(data_col) >= (1 - margin)*exact_value &
             !!sym(data_col) <= (1 + margin)*exact_value) %>%
      group_by(condition) %>%
      summarize(count = n(),
                frac_approx_correct = mean(approx_correct),
                se = sqrt(frac_approx_correct * (1 - frac_approx_correct) / n()),
                lower = frac_approx_correct - se,
                upper = frac_approx_correct + se)
}

# general function to construct an error bar of correct response percentages in each condition
plot_correct_pct_by_condition <- function(qtype, qid, title) {
    exact_value <- filter(exact_values, question_type == qtype & question == qid)$actual_exact[1]
    data_col <- sprintf("%s_%s", qtype, qid)
    plot_data <- compute_correct_percentages(data_col, exact_value, margin)
    
    ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = condition, y = frac_approx_correct)) +
    geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = lower, ymax = upper)) +
    scale_y_continuous(label = percent) +
    labs(
        x = '',
        y = sprintf('Percent of approximately correct responses\n(within %d%% of exact answer)', margin * 100),
        title = title
    )  
}

# general function to display all distinct responses and their frequencies in each condition
distinct_responses_by_condition <- function(qtype, qid) {
    actual_exact <- filter(exact_values, question_type == qtype & question == qid)$actual_exact[1]
    actual_approx <- filter(exact_values, question_type == qtype & question == qid)$actual_approx[1]
    condition_sizes <- (df %>% count(condition) %>% arrange(condition) %>% select(n))[[1]]
    print(sprintf(
        "Actual value was %s in the precise condition and %s in the round condition",
        as.character(actual_exact), as.character(actual_approx)
    ))
    table_data <- df_long %>%
        filter(question_type == qtype & question == qid) %>%
        group_by(response, condition) %>%
        summarize(count = n(), correctness = prod(is_correct_exact)) %>%
        pivot_wider(names_from = "condition", values_from = "count", names_prefix = "Frequency in ") %>%
        mutate(`Frequency in Precise` = coalesce(`Frequency in Precise`, 0),
               `Frequency in Round` = coalesce(`Frequency in Round`, 0)) %>%
        select(response, correctness, `Frequency in Precise`, `Frequency in Round`)
    
    colnames(table_data) <- c('response', 'correctness',
                              sprintf('Frequency in Precise (n = %d)', condition_sizes[1]), 
                              sprintf('Frequency in Round (n = %d)', condition_sizes[2]))
    
    table_data %>% arrange(desc(correctness), desc(response))
}

remove_outliers <- function(df, iqr_factor, colname = "response") {
    Q <- quantile(df[[colname]], probs=c(.25, .75), na.rm = TRUE)
    iqr <- IQR(df[[colname]])
    up <- Q[2] + iqr_factor*iqr
    low <- Q[1] - iqr_factor*iqr
    df %>% filter(df[[colname]] > low & df[[colname]] < up)
}

text_setting <- function(){
    theme(
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 16),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 16),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 16),
        strip.text.x = element_text(size = 18),
        text = element_text(size = 14) 
    )
}

Time spent¶

In [40]:
plot_time_spent_on_activity <- function(activity, trim_pct = 0) {
    time_col <- sprintf("duration_%s", activity)
    # histogram of time spent on recall page
    time_histogram <- ggplot(df, aes(x = !!sym(time_col) / 60)) +
        geom_histogram() +
        facet_wrap(~ condition, scale = "free_y") +
        labs(
            x = sprintf("Time spent on %s page in minutes", activity),
            y = "Number of participants",
            title = sprintf("Time spent on %s", activity))
    print(time_histogram)
    
    # bar plot of mean & sd of time spent
    time_barplot <- df %>%
        group_by(condition) %>%
        summarize(count = n(),
            mean_time_recall_page = mean(!!sym(time_col)/60, trim = trim_pct),
            se = sd(!!sym(time_col)/60) / sqrt(n()),
            lower = mean_time_recall_page - se,
            upper = mean_time_recall_page + se) %>%
        ggplot(aes(x = condition, y = mean_time_recall_page)) +
        geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = lower, ymax = upper)) +
        labs(
            x = "",
            y = sprintf("Average time spent on %s page", activity),
            title = sprintf("Time spent on %s by condition", activity),
            subtitle = "Trimmed 2.5% of outliers on upper and lower ends")
    print(time_barplot)
}

Consistency between implied and reported calculations¶

The idea here is to see if we can tease apart whether people are just having an easier time recalling round numbers, or if the round numbers are also helping their calculation. We can do this by comparing their reported calculation for a problem to their implied calcuation based on the numbers they recalled and check for consistency.

So for instance say someone recalled an urgent care cost of 100 and an emergency room cost of 810, and when asked separately to estimate that difference they responded with 700. Well call this last number (700) their reported estimate, and well compute an implied estimate from the first two numbers: 810 - 100 = 710. So in this way we can compare what they would have said if they only had error in recall but acted as perfect calculators using those recalled numbers (implied estimate of 710) to what they actually said (700). These are close (the reported estimate is within 10% of the implied one), so we could say theyre approximately consistent, but theyre not exactly the same, so we wouldnt count them as exactly consistent.

Percent approximate aggreement plots¶

Approximately consistent (within 10%)¶

First do this where match is approximate, allowing them to be up to 10% off.

In [45]:
implied_vs_reported_calc <- df %>%
    mutate(implied_calculate_enroll = recall_enroll_1 / recall_enroll_2 *100,
           implied_calculate_hondura = recall_hondura_2 - recall_hondura_1,
           implied_calculate_frick = recall_frick_1 / recall_frick_2) %>%
    select(ResponseId, condition, matches('^(implied_)?calculate_')) %>% 
    pivot_longer(matches('^(implied_)?calculate_')) %>% 
    mutate(implied_or_reported = ifelse(grepl('^implied', name), 'implied', 'reported'), name = gsub('.*_', '', name)) %>%
    pivot_wider(c(ResponseId, condition, name), implied_or_reported)

facet_labels <- exact_values %>% 
  filter(question_type == "calculate") %>% 
  select(name = question, question_pretty)

plot_data <- implied_vs_reported_calc %>%
  mutate(reported_is_approx_implied = reported >= (1 - margin)*implied & reported <= (1 + margin)*implied) %>%
  filter(is.finite(reported_is_approx_implied)) %>%
  group_by(condition, name) %>%
  summarize(frac_close = mean(reported_is_approx_implied),
            se = sqrt(frac_close * (1 - frac_close) / n()),
            lower = frac_close - se,
            upper = frac_close + se) %>%
  left_join(facet_labels)
